e BAD,$ $y = \\angle DAE,$ and $z = \\angle EAC,$ then find\n\\[\\frac{\\sin (x + y) \\sin (y + z)}{\\sin x \\sin z}.\\]\nAssistant: <think>", "response": "Triangle $ABC$ with point $D$ and $E$ on $BC$ such that $BD=DE=EC$ is given. Since $BD=DE=EC$, $\\triangle BDE$ and $\\triangle DEC$ are isosceles with $BD=DE$ and $DE=EC$. Denote the angles $\\angle BAD = x$, $\\angle DAE = y$, and $\\angle EAC = z$. We need to find the value of the expression $\\frac{\\sin(x+y) \\sin(y+z)}{\\sin x \\sin z}$. \n\nFirst, note that $\\angle BAE = x + y$ and $\\angle CAE = y + z$. Also, since $AD$ and $AE$ are angle bisectors of $\\angle EAC$ and $\\angle ABC$, they split the angles proportionally. Using the angle bisector theorem and properties of isosceles triangles, we can infer that the angles formed at $D$ and $E$ are all equal. \n\nSince $\\triangle BDE$ and $\\triangle DEC$ are isosceles, we have $\\angle BDE = \\angle BED$ and $\\angle DEC = \\angle DCE$. Therefore, the angles at $D$ and $E$ add up to $180^\\circ$. Thus, we can use the sine addition formula and the fact that the angles at $D$ and $E$ are equal to find the value of the expression.\n\nSince $\\angle BAC = x + y + z$, and given that $\\triangle ABC$ is divided into three equal segments on $BC$, $\\angle BAC = 60^\\circ$. This implies that $x + y + z = 60^\\circ$. We can now use the sine addition formula: \n\n\\[\n\\sin(x + y) = \\sin(60^\\circ - z) = \\sin 60^\\circ \\cos z - \\cos 60^\\circ \\sin z = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\cos z - \\frac{1}{2} \\sin z,\n\\]\nand\n\\[\n\\sin(y + z) = \\sin(60^\\circ - x) = \\sin 60^\\circ \\cos x - \\cos 60^\\circ \\sin x = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\cos x - \\frac{1}{2} \\sin x.\n\\]\n\nTherefore, the expression becomes:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{\\left(\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\cos z - \\frac{1}{2} \\sin z\\right) \\left(\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} \\cos x - \\frac{1}{2} \\sin x\\right)}{\\sin x \\sin z}.\n\\]\n\nSimplifying the product of the numerators, we get:\n\n\\[\n\\left(\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2} 